===Noun===
{{en-noun|+|equinoctes}}

# {{lb|en|astronomy}} The [[intersection]] of the [[apparent]] [[path]] of the [[sun#Noun|sun]] in the [[sky#Noun|sky]] (the [[ecliptic#Noun|ecliptic]]) with the [[celestial equator]].
# One of the two [[day]]s on which this [[intersection]] [[occur]]s [[each]] [[year]]: [[March]] 19–21 ([[spring#Noun|spring]] in the [[Northern Hemisphere]], and [[autumn]] in the [[Southern Hemisphere]]) and [[September]] 21–24 (autumn in the Northern Hemisphere, and spring in the Southern Hemisphere).
#: {{synonyms|en|q1=rare|evennight}}
#* {{quote-book|en|author=Clive L. N. Ruggles|title=Ancient Astronomy: An Encyclopedia of Cosmologies and Myth|year=2005|passage=Since it gets light before the sun rises and remains light after the sun sets, the actual period of darkness at the '''equinox''' will be substantially less than twelve hours, the exact amount depending on latitude and how one defines the boundary between twilight and night.}}
# {{lb|en|obsolete|rare}} A {{l|en|gale|t=very [[strong#Adjective|strong]] [[wind#Noun|wind]]}} once [[think#Verb|thought]] to [[occur]] more [[frequently]] around the [[time#Noun|time]] of an equinox ''(sense 2)'', now [[know#Verb|known]] to be a [[misconception]]; an [[equinoctial]] gale.
#* '''1687''', John Dryden, ''The Hind and the Panther''
#*: No more than usual '''Equinoxes''' blew.
#* '''1899''', Rudyard Kipling, ''Stalky & Co.''
#*: The '''Equinox''' drove the sand into their faces or round their legs, as they dived among the sheep-haunted hollows.

